<font color="#FF0000">REAL, DERELICTION OF DUTY!!!</font><br>
<tt>Sun Jul 27 19:03:24 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
IN RESPONSE,<br><br>
It should not, even today make a difference to the American fighting men who fought in Vietnam why we were there in the first place.  That is not the issue, it wasn't then. I was fortunate to never have found that bullet with my name on, though many tried.  <br><br>
As a military men you followed orders. Our Commander-In-Chief, the president of the United States ordered us to help defend the South Vietnamese government from Communist aggression and that is what we did. That is what I did. It is that simple.<br><br>
The problem arises not in the conscientious objectors right to feel as he does, I fought for his right to do so. <br>
The problem arises when that same contentious objector attacked us for doing our duty, when they tried to prevent others from doing their duty. When they turned around and condemned our actions as anything other then honorable. When they branded us as drug crazed - baby killers because of, I can only speculate, of their own shame and guilt. It was either that, or they really were not conscientious objectors.<br><br>
That is why so many Vietnam veterans remained and remain silent until this day. We did not understand why after we had done our duty, we were treated with such contempt. It was a shock to us, when we returned home, to see on the posters carried by anti-war demonstrators the same words and phrases we had seen and heard uttered at us by the communist soldiers we fought against.<br>
  <br>
That is what the Vietnam veteran has had to fight all these years. Not the war itself but the politics of that war. The unjustified labels inflicted upon us who only did as our country bid us to do. <br>

<p><code>--   (cook Barela) </code><p>


